Red Hat Identity Management (IdM) — Implementation Statement
Background
CSC currently manages Linux access control across a few different systems. Sudo privileges are defined in a GitHub repository and pushed to Linux hosts via AAP playbooks. SSH access is tied to Active Directory group memberships. Service accounts that need to bypass Duo authentication are configured individually on each host.
Each of these works in isolation, but none of them talk to each other and there is no single place to see who has access to what across the Linux estate. On top of that, sudo access today is broadly granted — most users have full or near-full sudo rights on the systems they touch rather than access scoped to what their role actually needs. That is a risk that needs to be addressed.
Red Hat IdM is the solution we are looking at to address this. It centralises Linux access control — SSH, sudo, and role-based access — into one platform. Worth noting upfront: IdM does not require a separate license. It is included in our existing Red Hat subscription, so there is no additional cost here.
Scope — Linux Access Only
It is important to be clear about what IdM does and does not cover in this phase. IdM is strictly scoped to Linux access control — SSH access, sudo privileges, and host-based access rules for Linux systems. That is all it manages right now.
IdM does not replace Active Directory. It does not affect Windows systems, applications, or any other tooling that currently relies on AD groups for access. AD remains the identity source and the source of truth for everything outside of Linux. Any existing AD group memberships used for non-Linux systems remain completely unchanged.
Today, access across the environment is managed on a tool-by-tool basis. Nutanix has its own AD group. AAP has its own group. Satellite has its own group. OpenShift has its own group. A new user joining the team could need to be added to 20, 30, or 40 AD groups just to have the access their role requires. That problem exists across the board and IdM does not solve all of it in this phase.
What IdM does is stop Linux from adding to that pile. Instead of Linux access meaning “add this user to these 15 AD groups”, it becomes “add them to their IdM role group.” One group for all Linux access, regardless of how many Linux systems or functions are involved. For new users going forward, Linux access is a single step. The AD group sprawl for existing users does not automatically go away — that is a separate housekeeping exercise — but it stops growing from day one.
What We Are Proposing
We are proposing a test deployment of IdM to validate the use case before any production rollout decision is made. The goal is to confirm that IdM meets our RBAC and HA requirements in our environment. If the test is successful, a production rollout will be scoped and planned as a separate effort.
The test environment will consist of two RHEL 9 nodes — one in DCE and one in DCW — running active/active replication. This gives us a realistic HA setup to validate against, ensuring either node can be patched or taken down without impacting authentication during testing.
Active Directory stays as the identity source throughout. Users authenticate with their existing AD credentials. IdM sits alongside AD via a cross-forest trust and owns the access policy layer for Linux specifically.
The VM build request has already been submitted. We are currently on hold pending a dedicated Linux EPG, which is needed to properly define the network firewall boundaries between IdM, the Linux hosts, and Active Directory.
The Problem We Are Solving
The core issue is visibility and control. GitHub holds the intended sudo state, AAP pushes it, but what is actually enforced on any given host at runtime depends on whether the last playbook ran cleanly and whether anything has changed on that host since. There is no definitive answer to “who has sudo where” without querying the repo, the run history, and the hosts themselves.
The same applies to SSH. Access is managed through AD groups, which means it is structured around however AD is organised rather than around Linux roles and what those roles actually need.
Sudo being too broad makes this worse. If an account is compromised today, the blast radius on most systems is significant because access was never scoped properly to begin with.
What IdM Changes
IdM moves access policy into one place. SSH access and sudo rules are defined once and enforced automatically across every enrolled Linux host via SSSD. No playbook runs, no repo changes, no per-host configuration.
Sudo gets scoped properly. A DBA gets database service restarts. An app team gets their application commands. An SRE gets the diagnostic and restart commands relevant to their work. Each role gets exactly what it needs and nothing more.
Service account Duo bypass gets centralised too. Right now that configuration lives on individual hosts. With IdM it is managed through a dedicated service account group — adding a new service account that needs a bypass is a single group membership change and it applies everywhere.
And the visibility problem gets solved. At any point we can query IdM and get a clear answer on who has access to what, what sudo rights they hold, and which systems they can reach.
What RBAC Looks Like in Practice
Access in IdM is built around three things — user groups, host groups, and rules. User groups map to teams or roles. Host groups map to server tiers or functions. HBAC rules define which user groups can SSH into which host groups. Sudo rules define what they can do once in.
A new engineer joins a team, they get added to the right IdM group, and they immediately have the correct Linux access across all the relevant systems. Nothing else needs to happen for Linux. AAP and GitHub stay in place for host enrollment and infrastructure automation — the change is simply where Linux access policy lives.
The AD Group Challenge
One of the more significant considerations in this project is the current state of AD group usage for Linux access. At the moment, a user may need to be a member of anywhere between 20 and 40 AD groups to have the Linux access they need across the estate. That structure has grown organically over time and reflects how access has historically been managed in AD rather than how Linux roles are actually defined.
IdM does not require us to restructure those AD groups. When the AD trust is established, IdM can reference AD groups as external members within IdM role groups. The approach is to create a small, clean set of IdM role groups — such as linux_admins, dba_team, app_team — and nest the relevant AD groups into them. SSSD and HBAC rules then work off those IdM role groups, not the raw AD group sprawl. The AD side stays exactly as it is.
The real work here is not technical — it is the mapping exercise. Someone needs to understand what each of those AD groups was created for and which Linux systems and access rights it was intended to grant. That knowledge may not be fully documented and may be spread across multiple people. Before we can design the IdM role structure properly, we need to do that analysis. This is part of what the AD group inventory effort will cover and it should be treated as more than just a script run — it requires input from the people who know how those groups have been used.
What We Still Need
Everything below is waiting on the dedicated Linux EPG project that Matthew is currently drafting for you to review and submit. Once that EPG is approved, the following will proceed in order:
Firewall rules between the IdM nodes, Linux hosts, and Active Directory — the port list is already documented and ready to go with the change request.
An AD group inventory and analysis — this is not just pulling a list of groups, it requires understanding what each group represents and how it maps to actual Linux roles. This analysis will form the foundation of the IdM role design and is a key dependency before any migration work begins.
Cross-forest trust setup with the Windows and AD team — a one-time step that does not change how AD operates day to day.
Future Considerations
One thing worth noting for a later conversation — tools like AAP, Satellite, and OpenShift all support LDAP-based authentication and can bind directly to IdM. If that were configured, an IdM group like linux_admins could potentially grant access to those tools as well, not just Linux systems. That would start to address the broader AD group sprawl problem across the whole environment.
That is not in scope for this test deployment. The focus right now is validating IdM for Linux access only. But if the test is successful, tool binding is a natural next conversation and could significantly reduce the per-tool AD group management burden across the estate.